<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06351123 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06351123 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; COURT; RULING; LIST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Other decisions today by the Supreme Court:; (box)Drug tests -- Justicesturned down an appeal by a man whose refusal to take a drug test cost hisbeing hired as an antitrust lawyer with the Justice Department. One appealscourt judge had warned that the original ruling could be used to condone drugtests for all people who apply for federal government jobs.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  OTHER ACTIONS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related article on this page.  </MEMO><TEXT>  (box)Hazardous waste -- The court agreed to decide whether states may imposelicensing and training requirements for hazardous waste site workers.;(box)Divorce costs -- Justices let stand a ruling that the $3 million in legalfees that Stanley and Dorothy Diller of Los Angeles were ordered to pay fortheir divorce did not violate their rights.; (box)Secret service -- The courtthrew out a lawsuit against two Secret Service agents who arrested a LosAngeles man they said threatened President Reagan's life in 1985.;(box)Military reservists -- Justices ruled that military reservists areentitled to return to their former civilian jobs no matter how long theirabsence for military duty.; (box)Illegal immigrants -- The court ruled thatthe federal government may prevent illegal immigrants facing deportation fromworking.; (box)Murder conviction -- Justices rejected an appeal by Californiadeath row inmate Kevin Cooper, convicted of four 1983 murders during what thestate's highest court called a &quot;nocturnal massacre.&quot; They let stand rulingsthat Cooper received a fair trial.; (box)Haitian identity -- The court ruledthe Bush administration may conceal the names of Haitians forced to return totheir native land after being denied refuge in the United States. The rulingexpanded the government's power to withhold information sought under theFreedom of Information Act. 